File: Minister of Employment and Labour Thulas Nxesi. JOHANNESBURG - Labour Minister Thulas Nxesi has announced a new minimum wage for South Africa. On Monday he announced that the national minimum wage has been increased to R23.19 for an ordinary hour of work. READ: New minimum wage for domestic workers on the cards The will increase by 6.9% increase comes into effect on 1 March. This would raise the salary of a domestic worker to R23 per hour up from R19.09 in 2021. The adjustments follow a recent proposal by the National Minimum Wage Commission to increase domestic worker salaries to 100% of the National Minimum Wage.